\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 1st to 15th April}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par Note: Readers are asked to remember that although this report is compiled as objectively as possible, opinions expressed may often seem critical and captious. This is because so-called "opinion formers" among the German population may often be ill info
rmed. PORO is not responsible for the views of the German population but is concerned only with the accuracy of the reporting.
\par 
\par 1. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 GENERAL ATMOSPHERE AND MOOD}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par The general attitude of the Berliners remained more or less unchanged during the first fortnight in April, Most Berliners find things quiet at present compared with the lively period at the end of March.
\par 
\par Although the discussions of the 3 Foreign Ministers in Washington concerning the future Western German State are being followed with in
terest in Berlin, they are not arousing much enthusiasm. Many Berliners do not consider themselves directly affected by these discussions, as they believe the decisions reached will apply only to Western Germany, not Berlin.
\par 
\par Berliners who are not well
 versed in politics fail to appreciate the importance of the discussions, for although they are acquainted with terms like "Occupation Statute", "Parliamentary Council" and "Basic Law" from press and radio announcements, they are often unable to explain w
hat these expressions mean.
\par 
\par Many are of the opinion that the work of the German authorities in Bonn is being too long delayed by Party interests and that the Western Powers acted quite rightly in urging this work on.
\par 
\par The majority welcomed the fact that Great Britain and the U.S.A. have succeeded in winning France over to a joint policy for Germany, and that the rebuilding of a German merchant fleet has been approved.
\par 
\par The visit by the British Deputy Prime Minister, Mr. Morrison, strengthened the Berliners' sense of importance. Mr. Morrison's words concerning Berlin were received with general interest and satisfaction.
\par 
\par A much discussed topic in the British Sector is the position of the population of West-Staaken, and fears are frequently expressed that the situation ma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1576440 y develop into a second "Stolpe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579  case". 
\par 
\par Criticism of the Berlin SPD is constantly increasing; in the opinion of many Berliners (among them a large number who voted for the SPD) the SPD is using its election victory to give
 rein to totalitarian inclinations. In particular, frequent criticisms have recently been heard concerning the economic, social and educational policies of the SPD.
\par 
\par Rumours which crop up here and there that the Berlin blockade is about to be lifted ar
e regarded with scepticism by most Berliners, Many state that such a measure could only have the aim of hindering the formation of a West German State and would therefore be a political manoeuvre.
\par 
\par 2. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 FINANCIAL WORRIES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par The money shortage is the Berliners' main worry at the moment. April is often described as the "black month", but it is generally hoped that the position will improve in May when the first full month's wages have been paid in Westmarks. The people are 
trying to overcome their present difficulties by the strictest economy. (Se}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1576440 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579  also item 9).
\par 
\par 3. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 FOOD }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par A remarkably large number of complaints have recently been raised about the bad quality of the dried potato issue, and about the prices for dried potatoes and vegetables which in the opinion of many housewives are too high.
\par 
\par The distribution of raisins and dried fruit and the announcement of a special Easter allocation of coffee beans for adults and chocolate for children were greatly welcomed by the population.
\par 
\par Numerous complaints were raised concerning the system of distribution of cereals. It was asserted for example, that noodles were issued for babies, whereas adults received baby food as their cereal allocation.
\par 
\par There is a large supply of canned fish in the shops, but most people cannot afford to buy these articles as the prices are claimed to be very high.
\par 
\par 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 . EMPLOYMENT WORRIES }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par At the beginning of April, an increase in the demand for employment was reported.
\par 
\par The strike call to the Western Berlin railway workers was in general rejected by the population.
\par 
\par The view is that nothing would have been achieved by the strike, which would at the most have resulted in a stoppage of West Berlin suburban rail traffic at th
e people's expense. The importance of a settlement of these wage problems, which are so urgent for the railway workers, is fully understood by the people, but they believe that a solution must be found by the Magistrat or the Kommandstura, not by a strike
.
 The creation of a voluntary labour service as suggested by Dr. Friedensburg, has met with a mixed reception. About one half of the Berliners are on principle against any form of labour service, whereas the other half considers the formation of a. volunta
ry labour service on pre-1933 lines to be quite sensible.
\par 
\par 5. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 ATTITUDE TOWARDS THE OCCUPYING POWERS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par It is noticeable that Germans often hold the Occupying Powers responsible for orders issued by the Magistrat or other German authorities, as it is believed that official decrees always emanate from the Occupying Powers.
\par 
\par The British Authorities' announcement that no flying boats would be employed in the airlift this summer was received with disappointment by the Berliners, as they had hoped that 
the airlift would be intensified by the use of flying boats during the summer months.
\par 
\par The destruction of the giant crane in Hamburg was described by many as an incomprehensible and senseless action on the part of the British.
\par 
\par Rumours that the manufacture of radio valves would soon be prohibited aroused considerable dismay in Berlin. In industrial circles it is believed that such a ban would throw thousands of skilled workers out of employment and valuable export orders woul
d be lost to Berlin industry.
\par 
\par The wish was frequently expressed that the Anglo-Americans should place one aircraft per day at the disposal of Germans; the German authorities should decide on the use of this plane. The control of business flights to th
e West would thereby be improved, and Berlin's relations with Western Germany could be extended by exchange visits on the part of politicians, business people, journalists, artists, sports personalities etc. Berliners think that too many of these opportun
ities were at present being lost because of Allied priority regulations.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par 6. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 DENAZIFICATION }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 The amnesty for juveniles and nominal members decreed by the Kommandatura, was welcomed by those interviewed and in the opinion of many sections of the pop
ulation was another decisive measure on the painful subject of denazification. 
\par 
\par 7. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 CLOTHING }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par 
\par The majority of Berliners consider that prices are still too high while admitting the supply and quality of textiles has been considerably improved. Many
 people stated, however, that the currency change-over would enable them to obtain new clothes when they received wages and salaries in full in Westmarks.
\par 
\par 8. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9838106 BLACK MARKET }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10486579 
\par Thu acute shortage of money continued to keep Black Market prices low.
\par 
\par It 
is noteworthy that recently certain goods which are obtainable in the "free shops" of the Eastern Sector especially soap powder, buns, frozen vegetables and strong bottled beer, have been bought up in large quantities in the Eastern Sector by Black Market
eers, and sold at excessive Eastmark prices in the Western Sectors.
\par 
